                <head>247. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On December 27, 1961, the Head of the German Section of the Soviet Foreign
                    Ministry, I. I. Il’ichev, handed German Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_KHS2"
                        >Kroll</persName> a long memorandum, apparently written by <persName
                        corresp="#p_KNS2">Khrushchev</persName>, outlining the Soviet position on
                    the world situation and Soviet-German relations in particular. The memorandum
                    broke no new ground on the question of Berlin, although it did allow economic,
                    cultural, and political contacts between the Federal Republic and West Berlin.
                    For text of the memorandum, which <persName corresp="#p_KFD1">Kohler</persName>
                    described as “obviously divisive in intent” (memorandum to <persName
                        corresp="#p_RD3">Rusk</persName>, January 1, 1962; Department of State,
                    Central Files, 661.62A/1-862), see Europa Archiv, Folge 3/1962, pages D59-70, or
                    Moskau Bonn, pages 876-877. A translation of the memorandum is attached to
                        <persName corresp="#p_KFD1">Kohler</persName>’s memorandum to <persName
                        corresp="#p_RD3">Rusk</persName>. For <persName corresp="#p_KHS2"
                        >Kroll</persName>’s account of receiving the memorandum, see
                    Lebenserinnerungen eines Botschafters, pages 537 ff.</p>
            </div>
